Introduction

The goal of this report is to train a machine learning model using an univariate linear regression model.

I will be analysing 3 key variables and their relationship with median house value:

  • Median income
  • Population
  • Number of households

Using linear regression analysis we can determine how each of these factors can influence median house value. The report will include an brief introduction to the dataset, cleanup of missing entries, modelling, an evaluation of the analysis, and a conclusion. The conclusion of the report will determine which of the three variables compared to house value provides the most relevent model.

Data Exploration

Dataset (Source: California Housing Prices)

The dataset contains 10 columns and 20641 unique entries, providing us a substantial data range. The data is taken from houses found in a California district and includes summary stats based on 1990 census data. The data used in the modeling for this report will be population, households, median_income, and median_house_value.

Column Names:

Describing the 4 variables:

  • Median house value - The dependent variable in the scatter plots, representing house prices with a range between $14,999 to $500,001. Based on the scatter plot graphs we see that a high quantity of houses are valued at $500,001, we can assume that the data cuts off for any house valued over $500,001.
  • Median income - A variable which represents average income in an area, ranging between 0.5 to 15.0. It displays a postive trend when compared with median house value.
  • Population - A variable which represents the total population in a region, with wide range from 3 to 35,682, with no strong correlation with house value when viewing the scatterplot.
  • Households - Represents the total number of households, with values between 1 and 6,082, showing no obvious correlation with house value in the scatter plot.

## Step 4 - Run three linear regressions (fitting)

# Import necessary modules from scikit-learn
from sklearn.linear_model import LinearRegression
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split
from sklearn.metrics import mean_squared_error

# Prepare the independent variables (income, population, housholds) and the dependent variable (median house value)
X_income = df[['median_income']]
X_population = df[['population']]
X_households = df[['households']]
y = df['median_house_value']

# Split the dataset into training and testing sets for each variable
# 80% of the data will be used for training, and 20% will be reserved for testing (test_size=0.2)
X_train_income, X_test_income, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X_income, y, test_size=0.2, random_state=42)
X_train_population, X_test_population, _, _ = train_test_split(X_population, y, test_size=0.2, random_state=42)
X_train_households, X_test_households, _, _ = train_test_split(X_households, y, test_size=0.2, random_state=42)

# Initialize and train the linear regression model for median income, population and households
model_income = LinearRegression()
model_income.fit(X_train_income, y_train)
model_population = LinearRegression()
model_population.fit(X_train_population, y_train) 
model_households = LinearRegression()
model_households.fit(X_train_households, y_train)

# Predict the target values (median house value)
y_predict_income = model_income.predict(X_test_income)
y_predict_population = model_population.predict(X_test_population)
y_predict_households = model_households.predict(X_test_households)

# Calculate the Mean Squared Error (MSE) to evaluate  accuracy of each model's predictions
mse_income = mean_squared_error(y_test, y_predict_income) 
mse_population = mean_squared_error(y_test, y_predict_population)
mse_households = mean_squared_error(y_test, y_predict_households) 

# Output the MSE for each model to compare their performance
print(f'MSE (Income): {mse_income}')
print(f'MSE (Population): {mse_population}')
print(f'MSE (Households): {mse_households}')

# Function to add text box with regression parameters and metrics
def add_regression_info(ax, intercept, slope, mse, mae, variable_name):
    textstr = '\n'.join((
        f'Intercept: {intercept:.2f}',
        f'Slope: {slope:.2f}',
        f'MSE: {mse:.2f}',
        f'MAE: {mae:.2f}'))
    # Text box
    ax.text(0.05, 0.95, textstr, transform=ax.transAxes, fontsize=12,
            verticalalignment='top', bbox=dict(boxstyle='round,pad=0.3', facecolor='lightblue', alpha=0.5))
    ax.set_title(f'Median House Value vs. {variable_name}')

# Scatter plot 1: Median House Value vs. Median Income
plt.figure(figsize=(18, 5))

plt.subplot(1, 3, 1)
sns.scatterplot(x='median_income', y='median_house_value', data=df)
plt.plot(X_test_income, y_pred_income, color='red')  # regression line
add_regression_info(plt.gca(), intercept_income, slope_income, mse_income, mae_income, 'Median Income')

# Scatter plot 2: Median House Value vs. Population
plt.subplot(1, 3, 2)
sns.scatterplot(x='population', y='median_house_value', data=df)
plt.plot(X_test_population, y_pred_population, color='red')  # regression line
add_regression_info(plt.gca(), intercept_population, slope_population, mse_population, mae_population, 'Population')

# Scatter plot 3: Median House Value vs. Number of Households
plt.subplot(1, 3, 3)
sns.scatterplot(x='households', y='median_house_value', data=df)
plt.plot(X_test_households, y_pred_households, color='red')  # regression line
add_regression_info(plt.gca(), intercept_households, slope_households, mse_households, mae_households, 'Households')

plt.show()

Evaluation

Median House Value vs. Median Income
  • Positive correlation (higher median income, higher median house value)
  • Large/Steep slope (41933.85), indicating a very strong effect on house value based on income
  • High MSE and MAE imply significant variance despite strong correlation, other factors also have an impact on house value
Median House Value vs. Population
  • Negitive correlation
  • Small/Weak slope, indicating little to no effect on house value based on population
  • High MSE and MAE as well as negitive and weak slope imply that population alone is not an ideal predictor of house values
Median House Value vs. Households
  • Positive correlation
  • Small/Weak slope, indicating a tiny increase on house value based on household count (House value increases by $19.34 per household)
  • High MSE and MAE similar to the other scatter plot graphs, indicating that multiple other factors are influencing house value besides household number
In Summary

Population and household numbers have little to no impact on house prices, the large mean squared errors and mean absolute errors in all models indicate that other factors not shown here could be important in further predicting house values.

Conclusion

To conclude the report, **the model with the best fit is clearly *Median House Value vs. Median Income***. This model is the most consistant with proving correlation, whereas the other two models which compare house value to population and households have poor correlation, small and insignificant slopes, and reletively higher MSE and MAE. The model comparing income displays a steep upwards slope with positive correlation which sets it apart from the other two variable models. The households models displays lesser correlation, but a positive slope, for every household the house value increases $19.34, which is small in relation to the value range. The population model has negitive correlation and slope, making the households model the second best fit, and the population model the worst fit. These 2 models have a significantly lower predictive power with higher MSE and MSE in comparison to the better fit, house value vs income.

Brief Insight:

It's important to reiterate that while the model comparing house value to income is the most relevent in this evaluation of 3 models, the MSE and MAE are still high. This indicates income isn't a sole factor that inceases house value, developing models on other variables such as total rooms or total bedrooms could be looked at as those factors could be more related to the value of a home.
